<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-551-054  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 551 054.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  June 11 1990 v9 n12 p18(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Supreme Court selects 12 to participate in Hermes. (Project Hermeswill send court opinions to third parties)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Taft, Darryl K.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Supreme CourtPilot ProjectsElectronic Mail SystemsInformation Services.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Supreme Court Selects 12 to Participate in HermesandM;The Supreme Court has selected 12 organizations to participate in a projectnamed after the messenger of the Greek gods to offer quick on-line access toits opinions.andM;The court will soon begin a two-year trial of the system, called ProjectHermes.andM;The 12 information-oriented organizations that will transmit the court'sopinions in electronic form include two news wire services, four legalpublishers, three legal databases, an electronic information network and theJustice Department.andM;Set to begin around the end of the June, Project Hermes is a two-year pilotproject to transmit, via modem, the court's opinions to third parties.andO;Hermes' objective is to provide copies of the Supreme Court's opinions inelectronic form moments after they are announced from the bench, courtofficials said.andM;The court's Committee on the Electronic Dissemination of Opinions developedthe project in response to requests from news and legal organizations.andM;The court selected the 12 organizations from among 20 applicants.andP;  The 12organizations include the Bureau of National Affairs, the CommerceClearinghouse, the Justice Department, Mead Data Central, the NationalClearinghouse for Legal Services, the Supreme Court Opinion Network (SCON),the Thomson Group, United Press International, the Associated Press and UUNetCommunications.andM;Each participant will provide its own computer linkup to Hermes throughequipment loaned to the court by SCON.andP;  Also, each will pay an annualsubscription fee of $500.andM;The opinions will be processed in an Atex 8000 Document Processing andTypesetting system.andP;  The files then will be sent to a Hewlett-Packard VectraPC, using the Atex &quot;Writer&quot; conversion software and written to a floppy disk,a court document describing the process said.andM;The floppy disk with the text then will be hand-carried to the Project HermesPC, a Compaq Computer Corp. Deskpro 386, for simultaneous transmission to the12 subscribing organizations.andM;The court will transmit opinions in the Atex Writer format.andO;</TEXT></DOC>